file-name: XC554689-CHAFFINCH MP3 SOFT DRINKS 12 April 2020 A3551.mp3
rmk: Typical 'full song' in the early part of the breeding season. Several male Chaffinches had adjoining territories where the recording was made. You can hear two others responding to the main singer by singing back - but only in the gaps between verses.  Although Chaffinch song appears to consist of very similar verses - and some references claim that one verse used in one part of the breeding season can be replaced later in the season by another - I find that the bird chops and changes its verses all the time. However, most verses sound very similar. Unless you pay close attention, you would not notice the differences between them. The main area where there is a subtle difference is during the ending. To demonstrate, listen to a set of seven verses from one singer. This clip is unedited - so the inclusion of four different endings in just seven verses is real.  The first four verses [0:02, 0:08, 0:15, 0:22] are identical. After the trademark opening of about four fast 'choppy' notes, the terminal flourish sounds, to my ears, like the French word 'monsieur' (use your imagination).  The fifth verse [0:29] has a sharper ending - I cannot fit a phonetic to this one.  The sixth verse [0:34] has the choppy opening but no flourish at the end.  The flourish at the end of the seventh verse [0:41] seems to end with the word 'rescue'.  The interesting thing for me is that, on first listening, you could consider all seven verses to be pretty much the same.

rmk: Although this clip is devoted mainly to the song from a Chaffinch, it also contains a Song Thrush song burst at the start [0:02]. The first Chaffinch burst (out of a total of six) overlaps with the Song Thrush. Over the following few seconds, the Song Thrush continues but then falls quiet, giving the Chaffinch free reign to deliver its trademark song at 0:16, 0:29, 0:43, 0:54 and 1:03. On eight occasions you can also hear drumming from a nearby male Great Spotted Woodpecker [0:03, 0:14, 0:20, 0:25, 0:39, 0:48, 0:57. 1:01]. Moorhen calls are at 0:22 and 0:34. A Hooded Crow caws at 0:43. Woodpigeons are present over most of the clip and wing-claps are audible at 0:02 and 1:01. A Willow Warbler manages to slip in a single song burst at 0:22 - just after the Moorhen. The Willow Warbler is rather faint, however.
Windy conditions. HP Filter 750Hz, -6dB. ME66 + Mixpre 3

rmk:
A selection of calls from an adult male Chaffinch on breeding territory on 13th July. The territorial double-note is a 'falling couplet' because the second note is lower in pitch. I transcribe it as 'dee feat'. Incidentally, although each rendition of 'dee-feat' on this clip contains both parts of the double note, from time to time a Chaffinch will drop the first half of the double note ('dee-') and continue with just the second note ('feat'). 

Classic contact notes - given throughout the year - come first. So there is a 'pink' [0:01; 0:04] and the same note doubled to 'pink, pink' [0:07; 0:15; 0:18, 0:26; 0:29]. The default territorial 'dee-feat' (also referred to in books as 'rain song') is at 0:10; 0:21; 0:31; and, five final repetitions, from 0:44  to the end. A Robin makes quiet ticks at various points [0:07 is where it starts, although overlapped by the Chaffinch at this moment] and a Wren gives a total of ten alarm chitters, beginning at 0:27 until the 42nd second.

file-name: XC420053-Chaffinch, Mistle Thrush, Crossbill, Crested Tit.mp3
rmk: A medley of early morning song from some mature coniferous forest in Norway. The opening song and calls come from one or more Chaffinches. In the background -  and throughout a large part of the recording - a displaying male Capercaillie can be heard (unfortunately, it is faint). Nonetheless, at 1:29 a Capercaillie can be heard in flight and at 1:41 one call is clear. Black Grouse feature in the background during the second half of the recording - but are hopelessly faint.  A calling Mistle Thrush is at 1:44 and Mistle Thrush song is clear from 1:55 to after the third minute. Crossbills are clearly audible from 2:57 to the end of the clip.

Copulation or attempt (1:19). Finally the male flies away.
